SIMPLE: tinker
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tinker
<hw>Tink"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Tink</er>,
because the tinker's way of proclaiming his trade is to beat a kettle,
or because in his work he makes a <ets>tinkling</ets> noise.
<ets>Johnson</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A mender of brass kettles,
pans, and other metal ware.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Tailors and
<xex>tinkers</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Piers Plowman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One skilled in a variety of small mechanical
work.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Ordnance)</fld> <def>A small mortar on the end of a
staff.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A young mackerel
about two years old.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The chub mackerel.</def>
<sd>(c)</sd> <def>The silversides.</def> <sd>(d)</sd> <def>A
skate.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The razor-billed auk.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tinker</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Tinker
<hw>Tink"er</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Tinkered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Tinkering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To mend or solder, as metal
wares; hence, more generally, to mend.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tinker</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Tinker
<hw>Tink"er</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To busy one's self in mending
old kettles, pans, etc.; to play the tinker; to be occupied with small
mechanical works.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tinkering</ent>⟦br⟧
